Spectacular "wingsuit" jump above Bogota
Sportsman Jhonathan Florez jumped Thursday from a helicopter over Bogota, the Colombian capital.
Equipped with a wingsuit, it passed at 160 km/h above the famous Monserrate sanctuary, located at more than 3,000 meters above sea level, where many spectators had gathered to observe its feat.
A black box in your car?
While U.S. road network planners are struggling to find the money needed to repair the crumbling highway infrastructure, many envision a solution in the form of a small black box that attaches above the dashboard of your car.
The devices, which record every mile traveled by a motorist and relay the information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt in Washington and in government planning offices to overhaul the outdated funding system for major U.S. roads.
The generally uninteresting sector of major axis planning has suddenly provoked a very lively debate and turbulent alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups to lobby for the government to use the little boxes to keep track of the miles you drive, and eventually the road you drive on, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The Tea Party is over.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses its concern about the protection of privacy.
And while members of Congress can’t agree on whether to continue, several states haven’t waited.
They are looking at how, over the next decade, they will be able to move to a system that allows drivers to pay based on the number of miles driven.
Thousands of motorists have already loaded these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS monitoring system, for an experimental trip.
This is truly essential for our nation.
“It’s not like we have a choice,” said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of the Southern California Association of Governments, which expects the state to begin recording miles driven by every Californian motorist by 2025.
There will be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
The technology is there to do that.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country’s Highway Trust Fund, funded with the taxes Americans pay at the pump, is financially drained.
Americans don't buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars can travel more miles with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax, even by 1 cent, while gas prices are high.
“The gas tax is just not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently had trackers installed on 500 cars to test a mile-by-mile payment system.
“It turns out to be the most logical long-term alternative,” he said.
Wonks calls this a mileage fee.
Not surprisingly, the idea appeals to city liberals, since taxes could be used to change driving habits to reduce congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to meet the goals set in the state’s ambitious global warming laws.
But Rep. Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he also sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
Reason Foundation’s free-market supporters also appreciate the idea of charging drivers by the mile.
“This isn’t just a tax going into a big black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they get.
The move is also backed by two former U.S. Transportation Secretaries who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to go the payment-by-the-mile route.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have involved about 10,000 cars.
But the House Speaker killed the proposal, responding to concerns from rural lawmakers representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to get to work or town.
However, several states and major cities are making progress on their side.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to conduct the most important experience in the country.
These drivers will soon pay the state mileage fees instead of gas taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is considering one.
Illinois is testing a limited number of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transportation in states along the U.S. east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida) is studying how it could implement the change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer motorists recently equipped their cars with a device, drivers were concerned that the government might follow their every move.
“Worries about Big Brother and things like that are a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, who heads strategic performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It's not something people want.
From the start of the trial, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full-fledged tracking devices.”
There is no need to build a huge and cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people's daily comings and goings.
Nevada is among the few states now scrambling to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car travels, but without knowing the exact location or time.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will be more comfortable.
The search for this technology has led some state agencies to call on a small California startup called True Mileage.
Originally, the company was not intended to help motorists who pay taxes to the states.
It was looking to break into the emerging auto insurance market, where drivers would pay based on their mileage.
But the devices it tests have appealed to planners of major axes because they do not use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, downloaded periodically by modem.
“People will be more inclined to do that if you don’t record their speed and locate them,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Major errors have been made in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are much less expensive and less intrusive ways to proceed.
In Oregon, planners try the experience by offering motorists different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They can still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a plan based on the average number of miles traveled by all residents of the state.
Other states hope to sell the concept to wary citizens by allowing devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transportation officials are looking to develop a taxation scheme that would also be equipped to pay for parking fees, provide “pay-per-drive” insurance, and create a real-time speed data set from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
"Drivers would be incentivized to participate because of the benefits the system offers them," said a town planning document.
However, some transportation planners wonder if the whole pay-per-mile debate is just a huge diversion.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission of the San Francisco Bay Area, officials say Congress could very simply handle the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by raising taxes on gasoline.
A single or additional annual tax could be imposed on drivers of hybrid vehicles and others whose vehicles do not consume much gasoline, so that everyone pays their fair share.
“There’s no need to resort to radical surgery when you just need aspirin,” Randy Rentschler, the committee’s director of legislation and public affairs, said in a statement.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will worry about their privacy and a lot of other things.
David Bowie: four unreleased songs
The English musician has not finished surprising this year.
Starting with The Next Day, released in January, he has concocted a luxury reissue scheduled for November 4, with several unreleased.
Four have already emerged on the web.
The announcement of the release of a new album by David Bowie had left everyone stunned.
On his 66th birthday, January 8, 2013, he said that a new album would be released in March.
After ten years of silence (the last record, Reality, dates from 2003) and too few appearances in public, the English musician proved that we could still count on him to make the pop scene sparkle.
A Feast for His Fans
Not tired of surprises, David Bowie had more than one trick in his bag with The Next Day.
The Thin White Duke will reissue the album on November 4.
For the occasion, he concocted a real feast for his fans.
This reissue, titled The Next Day Extra, will be available as three discs: the original album, unreleased studio sessions and remixes, as well as a DVD containing the four clips already unveiled.
The Next Day Extra will contain a total of ten additional tracks compared to the original album: the three tracks of the Deluxe edition, five songs specially unveiled for the occasion, as well as two remixes.
David Bowie also made the presentations of this beautiful box in a video.
He introduces both each of the records, but also the accessories provided with: exclusive photos and covers, a notebook to share his own impressions, a booklet with the lyrics...
And, above all, it gives a taste of his new track Atomica, typically in the vein of The Next Day, with guitars very forward and a rock electricity skillfully mastered.
Unreleased already listening
But Atomica is not the only title to reveal its charms.
The Informer, Like A Rocket Man, Born In A UFO are also available on the web.
The Informer is double-sided: a disturbing intro before a bright cavalcade that gradually slows down to give way to a pop ballad.
On Like A Rocket Man, did Bowie want to make a small reference to Elton John’s Rocket Man, or even Gravity?
With this playful title, the singer seems in his element when he no longer has his feet on the ground.
Space Oddity, next door, was much more serious.
On Born In A UFO, David Bowie once again makes reference to his strangeness: would he come from another planet?
The guitar riffs, mesmerizing, make you want to leave the Earth.
Bowie has fun in any case to play the chameleon with these titles: turn by turn informant, man on board a rocket, Martian potential...
He hides and reveals both, plays to adopt different personalities, as he has done throughout his career, including with his characters Ziggy Stardust and Aladdin Sane.
No wonder he has a mask in his hand in the photograph of the Louis Vuitton Invitation to Travel campaign, of which he embodies the new face.
It will appear in one of their commercials, broadcast from November 10.
Defence Minister Rob Nicholson insisted that wounded soldiers were not summarily released from the Canadian Armed Forces, and stressed that a transition process was being followed by all soldiers before they returned to civilian life.
Attacked by the Liberals and New Democrats in the House of Commons, Nicholson said that before their release, members of the military were following a transition plan in collaboration with their superiors.
All wounded soldiers are receiving appropriate care for their return to civilian life and none of them are released until they are ready, he said.
Critics accuse the government of wanting to save money by not allowing injured servicemen – who do not meet the military’s “universality of service” rule requiring staff to be able to perform a variety of tasks – to reach the 10-year eligibility period required for retirement benefits.
