Frontier Airlines plans to charge for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge passengers carrying carry-on baggage on its flights up to $100.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for carry-on luggage and $2 for coffee or soda, though in its announcement Wednesday, it indicated that passengers could take the unopened can with them to the plane’s descent.
The new carry-on baggage charges are for bags stored in the upper compartment, so small bags installed under the seat will always be free.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if the fees were paid in advance and $100 if travelers only paid once at the gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 fee was intended to encourage travelers to pay the fees in advance.
“We don’t want to charge that price,” she explained.
Airlines began charging for the first and second checked bags in 2008.
Passengers who tried to avoid these charges would put as much as they could into the carry-on bags stored in the overhead bins, so there was often no room left in these bins.
These fees are a way to ensure that passengers carry fewer things on board.
O'Malley said the new fees won't really be used to raise money.
It is about making it clear to the most loyal Frontier customers that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find space in the upper compartments.
Passengers who purchase their ticket on the airline's website will not have to pay.
Thus, a passenger queuing at a Frontier boarding gate could carry a bag for free, while the next person in the queue might have to pay $100 for a similar bag.
O'Malley explained that Frontier's website and check-in procedures are changing to ensure that passengers are aware of these fees before arriving at the gate.
Frontier’s hand baggage fees will not be applied until the summer, although no date has been set.
Passengers often snarl about baggage fees and other charges, but airlines love them.
They believe that baggage handling costs are significant and that passengers who want this service should pay for it.
Many people on Wall Street see the addition of baggage fees as a sign that airlines are charging enough to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
However, many of them did not pay for their luggage.
