The credit rating agency Standard & Poor's on Friday lowered Ukraine's credit rating, casting doubt on the ability of the former Soviet republic, in recession for more than a year, to meet its financial obligations.
The rating of the country's public debt securities moves to "B-", sinking into the category of speculative investments.
It comes with a negative outlook, with S&P seeing at least a one-in-three chance of it being lowered again within a year.
“It is increasingly unlikely that the government’s strategy will secure enough foreign currency to meet its high external financing needs,” the agency said.
