For two weeks, there have been almost daily reports of conflict between government forces and Renamo, the worst clashes since the peace agreement was signed more than 20 years ago.
Renamo was once a notorious rebel movement, initially supported by white-ruled Rhodesia and later the apartheid government of South Africa as part of efforts to destabilize the country's independent government.
After a peace agreement was signed in 1992, it became an opposition party.
Analysts believe the country should not fall back into open conflict, but recent events have shaken foreign investors and the local population.
The stakes are high for the growing economy as the discovery of huge offshore gas reserves and coal deposits in the northwest could attract more than $50 billion in investment over the next few years from companies such as Rio Tinto, Vale of Brazil, Eni of Italy and Anadarko of the United States.
Frelimo, the ruling party and the main political force since 1975, and Renamo mutually reject responsibility for tensions.
Renamo says the government is behind the recent clashes and launched an attack on its members in Sofala province, a traditional stronghold of Renamo, on October 17.
The assaults on the former rebels then escalated when government forces attacked Renamo’s bases and attempted to kill Afonso Dhlakama, the group’s leader, and Fernando Mazanga, Renamo’s spokesman, according to the Financial Times.
The government holds Renamo responsible for sparking the conflict, and accuses it of attacking soldiers.
President Armando Guebuza has sought to minimize concerns about instability.
