None of them knows how to negotiate well and none of them is ready to make the necessary concessions.
Renamo, which is in favor of electoral reforms, had already said it would boycott municipal elections due to take place in November.
Presidential and legislative elections are scheduled for next year.
Some commentators have interpreted his use of force as an attempt by an ailing movement to obtain concessions and a war chest from the government.
Renamo's share of the vote has been declining since 1992, while a new party, the Mozambique Democratic Movement (MDM), which was created by a former Renamo member, is expected to win more votes in elections.
Mazanga said Guebuza – who is due to retire at the end of his second term next year – wanted to destroy democracy in the country.
“He doesn’t want a multiparty democracy, he doesn’t want transparent elections, he doesn’t want peace because he doesn’t want to leave the presidency,” Mazanga said.
It is not known exactly what capacity the Renamo has, but it has carried out disruptive flash attacks on police stations and vehicles on a major north-south motorway axis.
