NSA spying: U.S. ‘goes too far,’ Kerry admits
The United States has sometimes gone “too far” in terms of espionage, admitted Secretary of State John Kerry, in Washington’s first admission in full controversy with Europe on the massive collection of data by the National Security Agency (NSA).
After ten days of scandal, revelations and denials between the United States and its European allies, this is the first time a U.S. government official has explicitly admitted controversial practices in the NSA’s interception of communications and data in Europe.
“In some cases, I concede to you, as the president has done, some of these actions have gone too far and we’re going to make sure that doesn’t happen in the future,” Kerry told a conference in London he was attending from Washington via video link on Thursday.
In his retransmitted speech, in the presence of his British counterpart William Hague, the head of US diplomacy has long justified the practices of intelligence and information collection by the necessary fight against terrorism and the prevention of possible attacks.
Invoking the attacks of September 11, 2001, the Madrid attacks of March 2004 and those of London in July 2005, John Kerry assured that the US authorities had since thwarted many projects of attacks, thanks to the interception of communications and the collection of information.
“We actually prevented planes from falling, buildings from exploding and people from being murdered because we were able to be aware of these projects up front,” he said.
And, John Kerry said to the Europeans, "I assure you that in this process innocent people have not been deceived."
But we strive to gather information.
"And yes, in some cases, it went too far in an inappropriate way," said the secretary of state, who had already had to speak about the international scandal during a tour last week in Paris, London and Rome.
He said Thursday night that President Obama was "resolute to try to clarify and to review these practices so that no one feels cheated."
But the controversy between Americans and Europeans continued to swell this week with new revelations in the press.
According to the Washington Post, the NSA was intercepting data from hundreds of millions of Google and Yahoo users.
The newspaper, which cites documents obtained from former NSA consultant Edward Snowden, says the program dubbed “MUSCULAR,” and conducted with the NSA’s British counterpart, GCHQ, allows these two agencies to retrieve data from the optical fibers used by internet giants.
According to one of the documents, some 181 million items had been collected in the month of January alone - ranging from metadata on emails, to text items or audio or video documents.
These interceptions would take place outside the United States.
But Yahoo and Google have denied any connection to these practices.
For the past ten days, several major newspapers in France, Germany, Spain and Italy have revealed that the NSA has massively intercepted data and communications from allies of the United States and their leaders, including German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Faced with the anger of European states and while leaks in the American press claimed that the American president was not aware of such eavesdropping, Barack Obama refused to speak about it, invoking national security.
On the other hand, the boss of the powerful NSA, General Keith Alexander, denied to him that his intelligence agency has captured tens of millions of communications from European citizens.
He even returned the bullet to the European intelligence services that would have seized these communications, before providing them to the NSA.
This would involve "military operations" in countries where these NATO allies are cooperating with the United States, and it would not be aimed at Europe at all, General Alexander said.
And the controversy spread Friday to Asia.
Indonesia has summoned the ambassador of Australia, whose mission is accused of being used by the Americans as part of a vast international espionage network that has also aroused China's ire.
