In his book The Death in Ashes, Damien Le Guay, philosopher and vice-president of the National Committee on Funeral Ethics, insists on the "violence" that cremation constitutes, for the survivors.
There is, with the cremation, "a violence done to the beloved body", which will be "reduced to a pile of ashes" in a very short time, and not after a process of decomposition, which "would accompany the phases of mourning".
There is also "a symbolic violence", which is due to the "effacement of the singularity and distinctive signs" reduced to the "anonymity" of the ashes.
Why is what is accepted without difficulty in some Nordic and Protestant countries still poorly experienced in France?
"Because cremation is a new fact," says Marie-Frédérique Bacqué, president of the Society of Thanatology and author of the book Taming Death.
It has only been tolerated since 1963 by the Catholic Church, which has limited attempts to tame it.
To tame cremation is for Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Michaud-Nérard, director general of the Funeral Services of the City of Paris, to provide for the deceased a ceremony as dignified as the one to which he would be entitled with a burial.
