George Kerevan: The break-up of Europe gives the choice to the Scots
Another day, another disturbing story of independence.
This time, we are warned that an independent Scotland would be required to join the European free movement zone in order to join the EU.
And now we hear stories of passport control in Berwick and a barbed wire border along Hadrian's Wall.
While it is true that Strathclyde's newspaper pointed to the possible economic benefits of greater freedom of movement with the rest of Europe, this was not in the headlines (and was to be expected).
Nor did anyone say that EU member states spend much of their time circumventing their formal rules when it suits them.
Since Scotland is not part of the Schengen area at the moment, a continued non-compliance with the rules would be a slim concession that Brussels could offer in return for anything it wants to get from the Scots.
So this is a story that is not one of them.
And a story so old it’s now frozen: I first heard the joke that “independence means passport control” more than 40 years ago.
Yet we have forgotten an interesting point in this interpretation of an old dusty tale.
Why should an independent Scotland follow the instructions of Europe, in fact?
Why exchange the yoke of London for that of Brussels, especially now?
Here is the real news about Europe: the great post-war plan to unify Europe is definitively at a standstill.
With the euro crisis, Project Europe is officially dead.
Across Europe, parties that oppose the EU or advocate abandoning the euro as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party, founded only this year and coming out of nowhere, garnered almost five million votes in the September federal election and removed the Liberal Democratic Party (equivalent to our Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been national opposition to the project of creating a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has marked a turning point.
The austerity imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, coupled with the burden on national economies through membership of the single currency, has led many to believe that Project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments running excessive budget deficits – this was only true for Greece.
Instead, the European system has imposed on its members exchange rates favorable to German exporters – something German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of a devaluation of the national currency, the countries of southern Europe find themselves with an intrinsic productivity problem vis-<0xC3><0xA0>-vis Germany.
The only recourse is to make dark cuts in wages and public spending – encouraged by Berlin.
Beyond the current fiscal and monetary problems, there is a deeper unease related to productivity in Europe.
Following the “green” energy policies imposed by Brussels – which are a reason to subsidize French and German companies in the energy sector at the expense of the consumer – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times more for gas than the United States.
This is a crippling disadvantage in terms of costs, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All the wage freezes in the world will not prevent the European petrochemical industry from being penalized by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, the revolt rages, especially in France, one of the EU's great leaders.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a passport to its political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy on Europe, leaving the French economy in shambles.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s far-right party, the anti-European National Front, has just won a crucial by-election, returning the Socialists to power in third place.
The National Front is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the vote – a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split of the right will automatically favour the left.
What is Marine Le Pen doing with her newfound popularity with the French white working class?
It wants to use next year’s European elections to create a single, anti-European anti-money bloc in the European Parliament.
If anti-European parties do well in these elections, which is very possible, such a bloc could control the European Parliament for the first time.
This is what I think: very soon, the anti-European and anti-currency sentiment unique in Europe will unify and eventually kill the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will return to something more like the free “Europe of (sovereign) nations” favored by General de Gaulle.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may retain the euro, but France and southern Europe will regain their own currency.
I expect the United Kingdom to distance itself from this project, and I hope it will be kind to the United States.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left behind in the Atlantic.
What about Scotland in all of this?
We can decide to be a region of little England (essentially).
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which includes sending Berlin and Brussels for walks.
I believe that Scotland could come to terms with a freer European agreement provided that we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries would be easier in a non-federal Europe of Nations.
Otherwise, we should imitate Norway and maintain our economic independence.
Scotland’s SNP government is – and it’s worth noting – the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe, winning a spectacular majority in 2011 based on its opposition to the dark cuts proposed (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor Alistair Darling and the Conservative/Liberal Democrat coalition that followed.
It would be ridiculous now for Scotland to vote for independence if it is to accept the austerity imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early Puberty: Ageing Early
Studies show that African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than white girls.
Physical changes don’t mean puberty is imminent
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible.
Experts believe the obesity epidemic could be a trigger for early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is not as pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in family and child health issues.
Should a mother be worried if her daughter’s breasts and pubic hair start growing at 7 or 8 years old?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics held this week in Orlando, Florida, Dr. Paul Kaplowitz, a pediatric endocrinologist, explained that these early physical changes are quite common among young Americans and represent a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents — in general, it doesn’t indicate a rapid progression to full puberty,” Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as bulging breasts, hair under the arms and in the pubic area, and body odors, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight advance in the age of first menstruation over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12 and a half, up from 12 years three-quarters in 1970.
“Once the breast has started to develop, it takes at least two or three years before the first period appears,” said Kaplowitz, also the author of “Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem.”
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty will develop.
There is debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but it is considered "early" when the development of the breast is accompanied by sudden growth before the age of 8 years.
In most cases, development slows down or stops – this is something a pediatrician can follow closely.
A more rapid evolution may justify tests carried out by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatments to delay the onset of the first period and prevent other consequences: premature aging of the bones that can slow growth and a small size in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug and hormone therapy are based on the child's age, development rate, growth rate, and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious with the drugs but acknowledges that “controlling puberty can alleviate some behavioral problems and the feeling for young girls to be different from others.”
The other big problem is understandable: Parents just don’t want their very young daughters to have their period.
“They fear the risk of pregnancy or even how they will handle hygiene issues,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter had her first period at age 10.
Even though there were signs and we talked about the rules, she wasn’t emotionally prepared.
She came home from school scared and upset to be the first among her friends.
There are many theories brought to the attention of the public about the causes of early puberty.
Yet there is no consistent theory that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages carried by the media are responsible.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz says the most credible hypothesis is that of the obesity epidemic.
He participated in a study of girls aged 6 to 9 years that linked the percentage of fat mass to the onset of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other influential factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach the age of puberty earlier than white girls.
There are various explanations.
Globally, the mechanisms of early puberty seem to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another problem: Although boys have younger facial and pubic hair, the trend toward true early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other physicians attending the PAA conference emphasized the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common, even in infants and toddlers.
“We need to be careful about how we identify the true onset of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist working at Goryeb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to ask their pediatrician for advice on how to talk with their child.
“It can mean having a conversation earlier than expected,” Kaplowitz explained.
If you stay calm, your child will generally react well.
Girls whose puberty is early need to be reassured that even when it happens sooner than expected, the process is part of life.
