How Biometrics Will Invade Our Lives
No more passwords to type to access his smartphone or pay for his purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers predict a future where we will be recognized by the biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, deputy general manager of Morpho, believes that "the century will be biometric".
Only biometrics will make it possible to ascertain the identity of a person carrying out transactions in a universe as transversal and transnational as the Internet.
Privacy-focused organizations confirm this craze for biometrics, but worry about it.
In 2011 and in France alone, the Commission nationale de l'informatique et des libertés authorised 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, the shape of the hand or the venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, canteens...
“Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere and anytime,” said Justin Brookman, head of consumer privacy at the Center for Democracy and Technology in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in some, and pessimism, in others?
Biometrics will be based on new techniques, which will make it possible to provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most used biometric data are fingerprints, the contour of the hand and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its limitations.
“For example, some people who work with concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are illegible,” says Philippe Robin, technical director of the identity field at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand suppose a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
This is both a security - one cannot capture this data without their knowledge - and a drawback: the procedure sometimes has to be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been carried out for about twenty years on other approaches, such as face or iris recognition (the colored part of the eye).
Thanks to the increase in the accuracy of the sensors and the computational capacity of the computers required for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has increased tenfold over the past five years, calculates Cyrille Bataller, Accenture’s director of R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the UK and Holland have deployed automated border posts using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
“Today, we are doing research on voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment,” said Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
A unique and unfalsifiable marker, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, director of studies, innovation and foresight at the CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers police a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and in one hour.
The uses of biometrics fall into two groups: identification (recognizing one person among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is who they claim to be).
Until now, identification has concerned the issuance of identity papers: biometric elements (fingerprints, photos, irises) must be compared with the information that the State has on all citizens already registered.
This helps to ensure that a person does not attempt to impersonate someone else.
This comparison principle may have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or store.
“We retrieve the images from the surveillance cameras and compare them to the photos of the celebrities that circulate freely on the Internet,” explains Dany Nassif, head of business development at NEC France, for biometric identification solutions.
Another use: take a picture of a quidam queuing in a store, track its progress through facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication initially concerned physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens, etc.) or logical access (opening a computer).
More recently, presence control has been added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the boyfriend pointing for another," justifies Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also concern transactions, in particular those carried out from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from certain distributors by entering your card and placing your hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the keystroke of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoul<0xC3><0xAA>me by the company Natural Security in partnership with banks and retailers: when paying in store with his bank card, the customer does not type his code, but introduces his finger into a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is scheduled to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Ways to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics appealing to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays at the checkout thirty seconds less, it is appreciable," explains the director of a large supermarket.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you customized options.
And, finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
“The fingerprints are stored on a first server; the identities of people are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which locks if you try to move it,” says Philippe Robin, Thales.
But, in the absence of extensive studies, it is impossible to know if these speeches really convince users.
Privacy experts, on the other hand, continue to be concerned.
“Progress in facial recognition, the proliferation of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance,” predicts Andrew Patrick of the Office of the Privacy Commissioner of Canada.
