Scientists have just shed light on how the movements of a dog’s tail are linked to its mood.
Previous studies had found that happy dogs moved their tail more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while nervous dogs moved it more to the left.
But now scientists say dogs can detect these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “Everyone knows that in humans, the left and right sides of the brain are involved differently in stimuli that arouse positive or negative emotions.”
Here we tried to see what it was like in other species.
He added that just as in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the messy tail movements of other dogs, the researchers followed animals watching movies featuring other dogs.
They measured the animals’ heart rate and analyzed their behavior.
It will surely not be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side and sometimes to the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: “We presented dogs with films that featured other dogs – either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other confounding factor – and we were able to tamper with the tail movement and present it as going more left or right.”
When the animals saw an expressionless dog wagging its tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog wagging its tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail veering mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog waving the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think the dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
Rather, he thinks that dogs know from experience what movements they should or should not worry about.
“If you repeatedly meet other dogs and you notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react based on that experience.”
The researchers say the results could help owners, veterinarians and trainers better understand their animals’ emotions.
Dog behaviour expert John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the University of Bristol's School of Veterinary Sciences, said this was not the first study to examine the importance of left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turned their heads left when they looked at an aggressive dog and right when they looked at a cheerful dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: “Dogs were more likely to go towards a robot dog when its tail moved to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite of what appears in the Italian study.”
He said the differences may come from the fact that the dogs that participated in the different studies did not fully consider the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs could be useful, he explained.
“Although many elements, found in different mammals, indicate that the two sides of the brain are being used for different purposes, many details still need to be worked out – and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviors can be recorded, it will surely not be long before we understand why their tail sometimes moves to one side and sometimes to the other.
