Pope Francis to appoint first cardinals in February
Pope Francis will appoint new cardinals from the Catholic Church for the first time on Feb. 22, the Vatican announced Thursday.
The cardinals are the highest churchmen in the Catholic Church behind the pope, and those who elect him, so Francis will appoint his first group of men who will ultimately choose his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, as soon as a cardinal reaches the age of 80, he can no longer participate in the election of a pope – this therefore falls to a group of 120 “cardinal electors”.
In a statement announcing the news, Father Federico Lombardi, a Vatican spokesman, said a meeting bringing together all existing cardinals would be held before the ceremony in which bishops will be elevated to the dignity of cardinal, known as the consistory.
“Pope Francis has decided to communicate his decision to convene the February consistory in advance in order to facilitate the planning of other meetings requiring the participation of cardinals from different parts of the world,” Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said that by February, the number of cardinal electors will likely have decreased.
He said that a pope usually appoints as many cardinals as it takes for the number of cardinal electors to reach 120 and as many cardinals over the age of 80 as he wants.
Next year’s consistory will be important because it will be the first since the election of Pope Francis in March this year, Valero said.
At the moment, there is a kind of tendency to favour Europe and Italy in particular.
“It will be interesting to see if the new pope appoints cardinals from the rest of the world to restore balance,” he added.
Forty percent of Roman Catholics live in South America, but a small number of cardinals represent them.
The cardinals will also be the first to be chosen since Francis formed the Council of Cardinals, a group of eight cardinals from around the world tasked with examining ways to reform the church.
In the past, the Pope made his own decisions.
“From now on, Francis has chosen these eight cardinals to help him,” Valero explained.
He added that it was “quite possible” for Francis to seek advice from the cardinals.
But we have never experienced such a situation – it is totally new.
Valero said the popes generally raised bishops representing large communities to the rank of cardinal, but that Francis was “full of surprises – so we don’t know who he will appoint.”
