An Obama Voter's Cry of Despair
I voted twice for President Obama, believing in the possibility of change
He says Obama has made laudable efforts foiled by Republican Party obstructionism
Obstructionism does not excuse the difficulties of the Obamacare site, nor the drone attacks
Obama's 2008 campaign memoir is a sad reminder of what could have happened
Nathaniel P. Morris is a 2nd year medical student at Harvard Medical School.
I’m reading an awfully sad book these days.
This is a book that, I thought, would encourage me during the sluggishness of the second year of medicine and give me hope.
It's called "The Audacity to Win" and it's a memoir of Barack Obama's 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finished my patients’ medical reports in the evening and went to bed, this book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions of people and speeches could take your breath away.
The election ended in a landslide victory and news anchors took time to reflect on the historical nature of the moment.
My comrades wept with joy and my parents kept all the newspapers they found.
A young team of visionaries was advancing toward the White House and the nation was ready for change.
During Obama’s transition period before he took office in 2008, he held 82% favorable views.
And then I close the book.
Returning to the present is a difficult awakening, it is like coming out of a dream.
It is difficult to remember these days full of optimism, they are like distant memories, a sad reminder of the opportunities of the past.
The change really happened in the years that followed the first time I voted.
It had nothing to do with what I had imagined.
I credit Obama with great accomplishments, from the passage of the Affordable Care Act to the departure of Iraq from our military, to the end of “neither seen nor known” and the assassination of Osama bin Laden.
In addition, I believe that partisan obstructionism has destroyed too many efforts to move our nation forward on immigration reforms, public health care, and the closure of Guantanamo, among other things.
But after repeatedly defending the Obama administration against my peers and colleagues, I can no longer provide an explanation.
I am on the verge of political despair.
The Republican obstruction cannot explain the wiretapping of foreign leaders, nor the attacks of innocent foreign children by drones.
It can’t explain the National Security Agency collecting data on Americans’ privacy, nor the indictment of whistleblowers who reveal the government’s wrongdoing.
It cannot justify the assassination of Anwar al-Awlaki, a US citizen, without trial, nor the evasion of public funding and the overspending allowed during presidential campaigns.
She cannot justify the findings of a report that says the White House’s efforts to silence the media are the “most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration.”
And, more recently, it cannot excuse the impossibility of designing a simple website for more than three years after the Affordable Care Act was ratified.
I don't know if that's what I was expecting.
If, at 18, I was supposed to understand that governance could contradict the political campaigns that preceded it.
Obviously, the electoral function is not predictable, because the opposition political party and events that happen by chance, such as the Newton massacre, influence our public conversation.
However, all of the examples I have listed above seem to be largely the administration's choice.
That's what bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confused and unrefined alternative that did not seem to determine his policies or positions.
I felt that Obama, elected to a second term free from the pressure of future elections, would keep the promises we have heard for so long.
Yet, while the index of favorable opinions has plunged below 45% this week, it is even more difficult to go back to the year 2008 through this book.
It makes me long for the many promises that have flown by.
This week, I read the part of the book that describes how Obama suffered huge losses to Clinton in the Pennsylvania primaries.
At a post-campaign meeting, he told his team that they needed to get back on track and stay true to their cause.
“I want us to focus on our talent,” he said.
We must remember who we are.
Here we are five years later, Mr. President, and I no longer agree with you.
The views expressed in this commentary are solely those of Nathaniel Morris.
