Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents at Danse Danse her two new group choreographies: the first inspired by the inks and poems of Henri Michaux, the second inspired by the famous piano solos Gymnopédies of Satie.
An evening that allows you to see the whole prism of Chouinard, from art to tics and from ink black to white.
A white screen serves as a background wall.
On the carpet, as white as it is, in the immense space that is the Thé<0xC3><0xA2>tre Maisonneuve, he steps forward, in profile, thin as a line and dressed in black, a body.
On the screen, an ink of Henri Michaux is projected.
The body, simple line, takes its form.
And this shape will be that of the whole piece: a thread of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, entirely dressed in black, only hands and face uncovered, wait on each side of the playing area, rush when the next spelling appears, embody it, run out.
This black and white game by Henri Michaux is done in a solo relay, in a group in unison (a mass that makes a solo), in a large group of twelve solos where each one executes its sign.
One thinks of "Gloire du matin", where, in solo, Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks written on cartels, posed in line at the front-stage.
It's the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here the music is loud, percussion and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the pace is always fast.
There will be breakage when Carol Prieur will take refuge under the dance carpet, to deliver, microphone in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of Michaux’s poem, monotonous and monotonous in the auction, and will continue dancing.
And the music to go back, and the sequence to resume.
This sound and energetic discharge, long, if possible, ends up deafening and numbing.
As does the regularity of the visual rhythm.
There are some beautiful flashes - image-making has always been a force at Chouinard - like those hairs that ruffle or those black fabrics that stretch the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
One has the impression that the choreographer, instead of going to meet Michaux's work, has imposed herself, with her tics.
The result: the bodies appear flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux’s inks, like Gestalt forms, open up a wider and more playful imagination than dance, more porous.
Only the end, in negative, with its dancers chopped by a stroboscopic light and white signs in a suddenly black theater, touches the magic.
The public loved it, the welcome was warm.
The Gymnopédies, after the intermission, is richer.
The stage is partly draped in grey, the dancers and a piano are covered with fabrics, like furniture in an abandoned house.
At the piano, dancers take turns playing the scores.
Their awkwardness in music, touching, give a real fragility.
On stage, pass couples, in love duets, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small transition solos, moving ensembles, choirs, writing is less binary.
Buffoons appear, also familiar to Chouinard, sporting red noses, in highly polarized male-female love parades.
Loves are carnageous, fugitives or gamblers.
Gesture, laughter and small cries beautifully transpose the archaic, grace and ridicule of coited bodies, beings that merge.
But the piece takes its real flight after salvation.
A clown returns to the stage when the audience leaves.
There, everything becomes permissible: the fourth wall falls, the explored universes are superimposed, the cabotin dancers descend among the spectators, gloss, smoke, short circuit, play codes of applause, stretch the sauce in a cleverly calculated disorder that remains sensual.
Joy and madness perspire, and it's Chouinard's art, there, to contaminate the public.
