He walks through mud, jungle and across rivers to offer free medical assistance
Dr. Georges Bwelle provides free health care in Cameroon’s villages
Dr. Bwelle and his team spend nearly every weekend seeing hundreds of patients.
There are not many doctors in this West African country, barely 1 per 5,000 inhabitants.
Vote here or via your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of CNN’s 10 Heroes of the Year for 2013.
You can vote for him, or one of the other 10 heroes, to be voted “CNN Hero of the Year.”
This person will receive $250,000 to continue their extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his ailing father alternate between periods of awareness and unconsciousness and went to hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only one broken arm, but he contracted an infection that spread to his brain, creating a hematoma that he would carry with him for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him abroad if we had had enough money.
Instead, Dr. Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to crowded clinics and hospitals, so he could get any treatment he could get.
“It’s not easy,” adds Bwelle.
You can leave the house at 5:00, rush to the hospital to be the first, and you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
People can die because they wait too long.
The situation has not changed much since the death of Dr. Bwelle's father in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor per 5,000 inhabitants, according to the World Health Organization.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is 1 doctor per 413 inhabitants.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroonians would not be able to afford the consultation.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and almost three-quarters of the country’s health spending is in the private sector.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” explained Dr. Bwelle.
And because of poverty, they cannot enjoy life.
After seeing his father and so many of his countrymen suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of things.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers have performed more than 700 surgical procedures for free over the past year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé Central Hospital.
And he has created a non-profit humanitarian association, ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, with about thirty people, they cram into vans after fixing medical equipment on the roof and cross difficult terrain to get to the villages that need help the most.
Luck doesn’t always follow them.
Many times they had to push the vehicles to cross rivers or muddy tracks.
But when they arrive, they are welcomed as heroes: the community throws a party, sings and dances and offers them the best housing available.
In these villages, free health care is a good reason to party, and Dr. Bwelle – with his big smile and boundless energy – is more than happy to join the festivities.
The next morning, the team began receiving hundreds of patients.
“We get 500 people each visit,” Bwelle said.
They sometimes live 60 km from the village, and they come on foot.
In this itinerant hospital, various health care is provided.
Many people are receiving treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive crutches, a collected pair of glasses or a free birth certificate – a document needed to go to school, but many poor families simply can’t afford to buy it.
In the evening, the team performs simple surgical procedures under local anesthesia.
The operations are usually performed in a school, a town hall or a house; after the intervention, the patient gets up and goes to the recovery room to give his place to the next person.
Through the lighting of the generator, the operating room and the sterilization of the equipment, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It’s a grueling pace, but village musicians generally help the team stay motivated.
“They beat drums all night to keep us awake so we can keep working,” Bwelle said.
On Sunday, the team returns to the city, tired but proud of the work they have done.
The group, made up of Cameroonian doctors and medical students, has performed 700 surgical procedures for free over the past year, and they know that their presence can make all the difference for those they help.
One man explained that the free operation he had undergone to treat a hernia would allow him to work again.
“It’s going to change my future and that of my family,” the man said.
In addition to maintaining this itinerant hospital and working as a surgeon in the hospital, Dr. Bwelle also works at night in private medical offices around Yaoundé.
It is this second job, he explains, which finances 60% of his association; the rest is covered by private donations.
“I don’t know when he’s sleeping,” said Katie O’Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer in Dr. Bwelle’s group.
He is still in the hospital or trying to find money for his association so he can run these campaigns.
For medical students and nursing students like Katie O'Malley, who come from the U.S. and Europe to join Mr. Bwelle on his missions, it's a field learning opportunity they don't have at home.
"We were able to participate in operations to help with blood smearing or to get the instruments to Dr. Bwelle," explained Ms. O'Malley.
It’s not something you get to do in America when you’re a second-year medical student.
Student volunteers generally pay for their trip to Cameroon, and often arrive with medical equipment collected.
But once in Yaoundé, their boarding, transportation and education are taken care of by Dr. Bwelle.
“He’s a hero, there’s no doubt about it,” Katie O’Malley said.
He gives his life for this association, and his desire to help the Cameroonian people is not nearly extinct.
For Dr. Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a challenge.
Helping others live happily by keeping the promise he made to his father is something that brings him immense joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” Bwelle added.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
Making people laugh and relieving pain are the reasons that drive me to do this.
Visit the ASCOVIME website to see how you can help.
The Two Frances by Pierre Nora
Perplexed, academics have long struggled to define and locate Pierre Nora.
Teacher in amphitheaters and classrooms?
No doubt, but pointing out his weakness for the cross paths, Sciences-Po, the Hautes Etudes.
Arbitrator of the works of others in his office on Gaston-Gallimard Street?
Indeed, but ignoring the hidden work and the underground writing of the editor.
Heir to the chair occupied by Fontenelle at the Académie fran<0xC3><0xA7>aise?
Of course, but knowing that such a coronation cannot replace the true holy oil, that of the thesis, of which it happened.
They readily recognized him as a great awakener, animator and unifier of their work, but pointing out that he showed little inclination to produce it himself.
To this uncertain image the monument of the "Places of Memory", to which he attached his name, also contributed.
Bad languages have seen a gigantic flea market, presented by an intelligent commentator, with a keen eye and weighted with scholarship, but incurably dilettante.
The two books published by Nora almost two years ago have already established that the one who passed for not writing had a lot and well written.
This book should definitely do it justice.
Yet we find, once again, the temptation of ubiquity, the intellectual vagrancy, the jubilation set to jump as if with feet joined from one subject to another.
But we quickly understand that the disparate objects gathered in this book with such a beautiful title bring the dealer back to one and the same passion: that of discovering the constitutive node of the French identity.
Why these dramatic calls for national unity?
Identity: This is an age-old concern.
Not long ago, we were collectively invited to give a definition of it.
But in the peremptory spirit of our leaders of that time, French identity was a timeless essence.
It was necessary only to deploy the accidents, and the case, Jacobinism obliges, was entrusted to the prefects and to the sub-prefects, authorized interpreters.
The one that Pierre Nora tracks is completely different.
He does not pose as the heir of an eternal franchise, he refuses the definition.
An analyst worried about a familiar strangeness, he wanders through a forest of symbols, stopped at every step by a rebus-shaped object, tormented by irritating questions.
Of which this one, which is born of the company itself: why, in a country so permanently settled in its borders, so anciently carpentry and solidly masonry, do we hear these dramatic calls for unity?
They are only so urgent, suggests Pierre Nora, to ward off the turmoil born of the discords of French history.
Franks and Gauls, Armagnacs and Burgundians, Catholics and Protestants: the forces of division here are very old.
And the most emblematic is obviously the one that splits national history in two.
Since the earthquake of the Revolution, the French have two histories and they have two nations, one monarchical, the other revolutionary.
The second wanted the death of the first, but without succeeding in denying it; on the contrary, anxious to rediscover its sacredness and all the more eager for unity and indivisibility as it had cut off the head of the one who was its obvious and powerful incarnation.
And, from there, an invincibly binary nation, divided between left and right, secularism and Catholicism, adoration and hatred of the revolution.
To make this singularity of French identity felt, nothing beats the four steps outside of France, so much so that Pierre Nora’s American escapade could well be the heart of his book.
Because America and France have both made a revolution, drafted a bill of rights, wanted to found a new society.
But the American Cousinship only highlights what is unique to us.
There, men who had left their Ancien Régime in England and no longer had to worry about it.
Here, men encumbered by an indigenous Ancien Régime, and all the more radical.
There was a consensual revolution when here she sowed drama and confit.
There are always honored founding fathers, and here revolutionary ancestors whose models are hard to make, and who have moreover killed each other.
There is an institutional constancy, and here a cascade of constitutions, as so many errors to catch up and attempts to resume.
The France that goes, the France that comes
There was, however, a time when the French believed they could sew the torn dress of their history, and defeat the curse of the number two.
To this Third Republic, central and creative moment, Pierre Nora showed much interest and even tenderness: saluting those who then worked to repair the revolutionary fracture, teaching schoolchildren everything that in ancient France obscurely prepared modern France and offering them a unified version of their history.
But this pacified identity has only been around for a while.
Here it is again under debate, shaken by a new type of immigration, threatened by the rise of demanding minorities, absorbed into the European space.
The book thus offers both the fascinating portrait of France as it goes and the circumspect sketch of France as it comes.
With, as a bonus, the portrait of the historian, who should reserve some surprises.
It turns out that the chimney was a housekeeper.
The man of multiple curiosities revolved, slightly obsessively, around the same idea.
The edge walker stood in the center of the center.
And the man who had deposited more than half a century ago a subject on the idea of nation, but had evaded the initiatory exercise of the thesis, confides to us, cum grano salis, that he will have finally done it.
Certainly in a less steep, more exploded and more subtle form.
But make no mistake about it, just as binding.
For much more than the imposed figure of the university curriculum, this thesis says the inner necessity of a life.
