John Kerry has admitted that U.S. spying “went too far inappropriately.”
Kerry said the U.S. defense posture toward its surveillance programs has been softened by admitting, unprecedentedly, that on several occasions, spying “went too far inappropriately.”
The Secretary of State also admitted that he, like Barack Obama, ruled on “autopilot” when a series of incendiary revelations by whistleblower Edward Snowden about NSA spying activities came to light.
The leaks have put the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic storm with its allies.
Speaking at an intergovernmental conference in London via video link, Kerry said: "It is undeniable that the President, myself and other members of the government have become aware of certain things in autopilot mode because we had the possibility, from the Second World War and up to the difficult years of the Cold War and then of course 9/11."
He then became the first high-ranking member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. spying had gone beyond limits, but insisted that everyone’s rights had not been violated.
He said: “In some cases, it went too far inappropriately.”
And the President is committed to trying to clarify and make clear to people that he was now conducting a thorough review of these practices so that no one would feel cheated.
I assure you that innocent people will not be abused in this process.
Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a force acting for good and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added: “We live in a new world where people are ready to blow themselves up.”
There is a radical extremism in the world that is determined to try to kill people, blow them up and attack governments.
What if you could intercept their communications and stop them before they act?
We did prevent planes from falling, buildings from exploding and people from being murdered because we were able to learn the facts in advance.
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to address concerns about the alleged U.S. spying case and convince Europeans of the need to continue joint counterterrorism efforts with the United States, the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy of Connecticut said he had spoken to members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about threats they had made about a possible withdrawal of anti-terrorist organizations because of the frustration with the National Security Agency's surveillance.
“It’s really important for the protection of national security in the United States that Europeans stand by us in mutual engagement in the fight against terrorism,” Murphy, a Democrat serving his first term and chairman of the U.S. Senate’s subcommittee on European Affairs, said in an interview from Washington.
And I’m going to go to Europe to make them understand that we must continue to work together to fight terrorism, despite the anger provoked by the NSA programs.
The press reports that the NSA has captured millions of communications in Europe, which has strained relations with some U.S. allies, however the agency’s director said this week that it was inaccurate and that it was a misunderstanding because it concerned metadata that NATO allies had collected and shared with the United States.
Other revelations included documents leaked by Snowden that the NSA had intercepted data and communications from German Chancellor Angela Merkel’s mobile phone and those of 34 other heads of state.
Intelligence Director James Clapper justified the spying by saying it was necessary and was a common practice on both sides.
In that tumultuous atmosphere, Murphy said his office is planning a congressional trip, which is expected to take place this year, and he hopes the delegation will include members from both parties and both houses.
The names of the other participating legislators are expected to be revealed in the coming days.
He said the route was yet to be determined.
Murphy said the purpose of this trip was to improve relationships, but also to show “affectionate firmness.”
He explained that European heads of state must be honest with their citizens about the kind of spying programs they have been running themselves for years.
“We can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, but they also need to understand that we are not the only one in the world doing espionage,” Murphy said.
In the meantime, Kerry is scheduled to travel this weekend to the Middle East and Poland to deal with the rancor engendered by U.S. strategies in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as U.S. surveillance activities.
